As part of Project 1, the steps of an unknown person were analyzed. Through a personal activity monitoring device, the amount of steps were counted throughout intervals of 5 minutos each day. These intervals start in 0 everyday for two months, October 1st through December 1st for a total of 17,568 observations. This report include the libraries and code utilized to read, evaluate, graph and analyze the data as needed for this project.

The following libraries were used:

library(tidyverse)
library(rio)
library (dplyr)

What is the mean total number of steps taken per day?

A new dataset was created to agregate the daily steps

daily_steps <- steps %>%
  group_by(date) %>%   
  summarise(total_steps = sum(steps, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

Mean and median were calculated for the total daily steps

stats <- daily_steps %>%
  summarise(
    mean   = mean(total_steps, na.rm = TRUE),
    median = median(total_steps, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

stats
## # A tibble: 1 Ã 2
##    mean median
##   <dbl>  <int>
## 1 9354.  10395
ggplot(daily_steps, aes(x = date, y = total_steps)) +
  geom_col(fill = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "Total steps per day",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Total number of steps"
  )

What is the average daily activity pattern?

interval_mean <- steps %>%
  group_by(interval) %>%
  summarise(mean_steps = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE))
ggplot(interval_mean, aes(x = interval, 
                  y = mean_steps)) +
  geom_line(color = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "Average steps per day",
    x = "Time intervals",
    y = "Mean steps by interval"
  )

About missing values

Amount of missing values in âstepsâ variable

steps |>
  filter(is.na(steps)) |>
  nrow()
## [1] 2304

Create new variable within main dataframe âstepsâ with the calculated mean by time interval

steps2 <- steps |>
  group_by(interval) |>
  mutate(mean_steps = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE)) |>
  ungroup()

Substitute missing values in âstepsâ variable with the corresponding mean value

steps2 <- steps2 |>
  mutate(steps = if_else(is.na(steps), mean_steps, steps))

Sum the daily steps using the new dataset âsteps2â, and graph the total steps for each day

daily_steps2 <- steps2 %>%
  group_by(date) %>%   
  summarise(total_steps = sum(steps, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

ggplot(daily_steps2, aes(x = date, y = total_steps)) +
  geom_col(fill = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "Total steps per day",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Total number of steps"
  )

Mean and median from the new dataset âsteps2â

stats2 <- daily_steps2 %>%
  summarise(
    mean_total   = mean(total_steps, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_total = median(total_steps, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

stats2
## # A tibble: 1 Ã 2
##   mean_total median_total
##        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1     10766.       10766.

Since the missing values were filled using the corresponding mean value observed in each day of the two month sample, the overall daily mean and median changed. In the original dataframe âstepsâ, a mean of 9,354.23 steps and median of 10,395 steps was observed. In the edited dataframe âsteps2â, both mean and median were 10,766.19 steps. This means that missing values in the âstepâ variable created a slight bias to the right while the median almost didnât change. This highlights the importance of evaluating measures of central tendency to understand what changes should be corrected in the original data as part of the data analysis.

steps2 <-

Group weekdays by âweekdayâ and âweekendâ

steps2 <- steps2 |>
  mutate(day_category = case_when(
    day_name %in% c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday") ~ "Weekday",
    day_name %in% c("Saturday", "Sunday") ~ "Weekend",
    .default = "Unknown"
  ))

Calculate a new mean for weedays and weekends

steps2 <- steps2 %>%
  group_by(interval, day_category) %>%
  summarise(mean_steps = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'interval'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Graph mean steps by interval and day category of weekend and weekday

ggplot(steps2, aes(x = interval, 
                  y = mean_steps,
                  group = day_category,
                  colour = factor(day_category, labels = c("Weekday", "Weekend"))
                  )) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    title = "Average steps per day",
    x = "Time intervals",
    y = "Mean steps by interval",
    colour = "Week day"
  )

It is evident that thereâs a difference according the category of the day. More activity was observed through the day on weekends, while steps go a little higher during weekdays only early in the morning and late in the afternoon. It is suggested to convert x-axis into hours of the day for more specific interpretation of these times.
